The connection types are filled with assertions that connection types are non-abstract subclasses of `Node` (such as "`ObjectTypes in a edge have to be Nodes`"); but `Node` itself *should* be perfectly valid. It allows you to create general connections to multiple `Node` subtypes which can be expanded with fragments.

For example:

```graphql
type Foo implements Node {
  id: ID!
  myFoo: String!
}
type Bar implements Node {
  id: ID!
  myBar: String!
}
type NodeEdge {
  node: Node
  cursor: String!
}
type NodeConnection {
  pageInfo: PageInfo!
  edges: [NodeEdge]
}
type Viewer {
  foosAndBars: NodeConnection
}
type Query {
  node(id: ID!): Node
  viewer: Viewer!
}
```

Queried via:
```graphql
query {
  viewer {
    myFoosAndBars {
      edges {
        node {
          id
          ...on Foo {
            myFoo
          }
          ...on Bar {
            myBar
          }
        }
      }
    }
  }
}
```

